    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nThe `on_bytes` callback doesn't fire if a buffer's underlying file is modified outside of Neovim, despite its contents changing.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n- create this `minimal.lua`:\n\n```lua\nlocal tmpfile = vim.fn.tempname()\nvim.fn.writefile({ \"initial content\" }, tmpfile)\n\nvim.cmd(\"edit \" .. tmpfile)\n\nlocal on_bytes_fired = false\nvim.api.nvim_buf_attach(0, false, {\n  on_bytes = function() on_bytes_fired = true end\n})\n\nvim.fn.writefile({ \"new content\" }, tmpfile)\n\nvim.cmd(\"checktime\")\n\nassert(vim.deep_equal(\n  vim.api.nvim_buf_get_lines(0, 0, -1, false),\n  { \"new content\" }\n))\n\n-- ðŸ’¥ The buffer content has changed, but on_bytes did not fire.\nassert(on_bytes_fired)\n```\n\n- run `nvim --clean -u minimal.lua`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`on_bytes` is called every time the buffer is modified, irrespective of the edit's origin.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.12.0-nightly+a04c73c\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 15\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nGhostty\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nghostty\n\n### Installation\n\nNix flake",
